\chapter{The methodology of parallel memetic algorithms designing}
\chaptermark{The methodology of...}
\thispagestyle{empty}

The chapter presents the methodology of
parallel algorithm designing based on memetic approach (Lamarck
and Baldwin evolution theory) making use of specific properties of
the problem and distributed island model. This approach is
presented on the example of the single machine scheduling problem
with earliness/tardiness penalties.

\section{Introduction}

%\subsection{Memetic Algorithm}\index{Memetic Algorithm, MA}

The memetic algorithm is an evolutionary approach based on the
process of natural evolution adhering to the principles of natural
selection, crossover and survival. The Lamarck's model
\cite{Michalewicz} of evolution is applied to intensify the
optimization process. In each generation a certain part of the
population is replaced by their local minima simulating a learning
effect which can be succeeded by the next generation as a 'meme'.
From the current population some subset is drawn. Each individual
of this subset is a starting solution for the local optimization
algorithm. Thus, there are five essential steps of the memetic
algorithm:
\begin{enumerate}
\itemsep -1pt \item \emph{selection} -- choosing some subset of
individuals, so-called parents, \item \emph{crossover} --
combining parts from pairs of parents to generate new ones, \item
\emph{mutation} -- transformation that creates a new individual by
small changes applied to an existing one taken from the
population, \item \emph{learning} -- an individual is improved
(e.g. by a local optimization), \item \emph{succession} --
determining the next generation's population.
\end{enumerate}
New individuals created by crossover or mutation replace all or a
part of the old population. The process of evaluating fitness and
creating a new population generation is repeated until a
termination criterion is achieved.

Similar to the GA, following kinds of parallelization are usually
applied to memetic algorithms MAs:
\begin{itemize}
\itemsep -2pt \item global parallelization,

\item independent runs,

\item island model,

\item diffusion model,
\end{itemize}
with similar properties as applied to the classic GA.
Additionally, a local search procedure can be parallelized in MA.
Such an approach is proposed by \cite{Berger} and applied to the
Vehicle Routing Problem with Time Windows (VRPTW) by using a
master-slave parallel approach. The master controls the memetic
algorithm execution, synchronizes and handles parent selection
while the slaves execute genetic operations together with local
search in parallel. Parallel memetic algorithm was also considered
by \cite{Bradwell} (asynchronous MA) and \cite{Tang} (MA based on
population entropy).


Implementation of algorithms which are based on multithread
multiple-walk searching\index{multithread!multiple-walk searching}
of the solutions space are usually coarse-grained application,
i.e. they require sparse communication and synchronization. These
type of algorithms are easy to be applied in distributed
calculation systems, as clusters which express beneficial
efficiency-to-price ratio. Apart from speeding up the
calculations, it is possible to improve quality of obtained
results. Search processes can be either independent or
cooperative.

\subsection{Independent searching threads}

In this category we can distinguish two base approaches:
%
\begin{itemize}
\item Researching of the solution space by using multiple
trajectories, which begin from different starting solutions (or
different starting populations in the case of using
population-based approaches). Searching threads can use either the
same or different strategies, i.e. the same or different local
search algorithms, the same or different parameters (tabu list
length, population size, etc.). Trajectories can cross themselves
in one or more places of the neighborhood graph.

\item Parallel researching of subgraphs of a neighborhood graph
obtained by decomposition of the problem into a few subproblems
(for example fixing of some variables). Subgraphs of the
neighborhood graph are searched concurrently without crossing
search trajectories. We obtain partitioning of the neighborhood
graph into disjoint subgraphs.
\end{itemize}

The first parallel implementation of the tabu search
method\index{method!tabu search} based on multiple-walk searching
of the solution space was proposed by Taillard for the quadric
assignment problem (QAP) \cite{Tail_paral_QAP} and the job shop
problem \cite{Tail_paral_jobshop}. The multiple-walk
parallelization strategy based on independent searching threads is
easy in implementation and one can obtain good values of the
speedup\index{speedup} under condition of proper decomposition of
the solution space into searching threads (and their
trajectories).

%If the decomposition is done improperly, a parallel algorithm can
%multiple search through the same regions of the solution space,
%i.e. we obtain redundance of searching.


\subsection{Cooperative searching threads}\label{koop}

This model constitutes the most general and promising type of
solution space searching strategy by using parallel
metaheuristics, however it requires knowledge of solving problem
specificity. 'Cooperative' means here the interchange of
information -- experience of searching history up to now. Specific
information, which is characteristic for the problem and the
method (i.e. the best solution found so far, elite solutions, the
frequency of moves, tabu lists, backtrack-jump list,
subpopulations and their sizes,~etc.) has to be exchanged or
broadcasted.

Information shared by search processes can be stored as global
variables kept in the \textit{shared memory} or as records in the
local memory of the dedicated central processor which communicates
with all other processors providing them with requested data. In
the model, in which processes cooperate with each other and
information gathered during moving along a trajectory is used to
improve other trajectories, not only can one expect convergence of
such a parallel algorithm, but also founding in the same time a
better solution than the parallel algorithm without communication
can takes place. In such a case we can say that cooperative
concurrent algorithms constitute a new class of algorithms in
deed.

The first heuristic algorithm of this type was asynchronous
parallel tabu search algorithm proposed by Crainic, Toulouse and
Gendreau \cite{61}. Packages such as ParSA \cite{116} offer ready
implementations of parallel simulated annealing algorithms based
on cooperative searching threads. The interaction strategy is also
very efficient in implementation of parallel genetic algorithms
(in the sense of obtained solutions). There are plenty of ready
libraries such as POOGAL \cite{31}. The majority of cooperative
implementations of parallel genetic algorithm is based on the
\textit{migration island model}. Each process has its own
subpopulation exchanging from time to time a number of individuals
(usually the best -- elite) with other processes (Bubak and Sowa
\cite{31}, Crainic and Toulouse \cite{Crainic}).
Bo\.{z}ejko~\cite{bozejko2009_2} proposed a parallel
path-relinking metaheuristics based on the parallel scatter search
algorithm.


\subsection{The problem}\label{section_twet}

This paper aim is to present parallel memetic approach on the
instance of a strongly NP-hard scheduling problem. We additionally
assume that the considered problem has \emph{no idle} constraint
(\emph{TWET-no-idle} problem), which means that the machine works
without stops. The problem of scheduling with earliness and
tardiness (total weighted earliness/tardiness problem,
\emph{TWET}) is one of the most frequently considered in
literature. In this problem each job from a set $\st{J} =
\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$ has to be processed, without interruption, on a
machine, which can execute at most one job in each moment. By $p_i
$ we represent the execution time of a job $i \in \st{J}$, and by
$e_i $ and $d_i $ we mean an adequately demanded earliest and
latest moment of the finishing processing of a job. If scheduling
of jobs is established and $C_i $ is the moment of finishing a job
$i$, then we call $E_i = \max \{0,e_i - C_i \}$ an
\textit{earliness} and $T_i = \max \{0,C_i - d_i \}$ a
\textit{tardiness}. The expression $u_i E_i + w_i T$ is the
\textit{cost} of execution a job, where $u_i $ and $w_i $ ($i \in
\st{J})$ are nonnegative coefficients of a goal function. The
problem consists in minimizing a sum of costs of jobs, that is to
find a job sequence $\pi^* \in \Phi_n$ such that for the goal
function
\begin{equation}
F(\pi) = \sum_{i = 1}^n {(u_{\pi(i)} E_{\pi(i)} + w_{\pi(i)}
T_{\pi(i)} )},\;\;\; \pi \in \Phi_n,
\end{equation}
\noindent we have
\begin{equation}
F(\pi^*) = \min_{\pi \in \Phi_n} F(\pi).
\end{equation}
%
This problem is represented by $1\vert \vert \sum {(u_i E_i + w_i
T_i )} $ in literature and it belongs to a strongly
NP-hard\index{NP-hard problem!strongly} class (if we assume $u_i =
0$, $i = 1,2,\;\ldots\;,n$, we will obtain a strongly
NP-hard\index{NP-hard problem!strongly} problem $1\vert \vert \sum
{w_i T_i } $ - Lenstra et al. \cite{lenstra}). Baker and Scudder
\cite{Bak} proved, that there can be an idle time in an optimal
solution (jobs need not to be processed directly one after
another), that is $C_{\pi(i + 1)} - p_{\pi(i + 1)} \ge C_{\pi(i)}
$, $i = 1,2,\ldots,n - 1$. Solving the problem amounts to
establishing a sequence of jobs and its starting times. Hoogeven
and van de Velde \cite{hoo} proposed an algorithm based on the
branch and bound method. Because of exponentially growing
computation time, this algorithm can be applied only to solve
instances where the number of jobs is not greater than 20.
Therefore, in practice almost always approximate algorithms are
used. The best ones are based on artificial intelligence methods.
Calculations are performed in two stages.
\begin{itemize}\itemsep -2pt  \item Determining the scheduling of jobs (with
no idle times). \item Establishing optimal starting times of jobs.
\end{itemize}

\noindent Bo\.{z}ejko and Wodecki \cite{boz_2005_3} proposed a
parallel coevolutionary algorithm for the considered problem.

